  <rdf:Description rdf:about="http://example.org/ontology#ITN259">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://example.org/ontology#Interaction"/>
    <rdfs:label>ITN259</rdfs:label>
    <hasClinicalEffects>Reduced antibacterial activity may occur, leading to incomplete treatment of urinary tract infections.</hasClinicalEffects>
    <hasInteractionDescription>Carbonic anhydrase inhibitors reduce the effectiveness of Nitrofurantoin by making the urine less acidic. Nitrofurantoin works better in acidic urine.</hasInteractionDescription>
    <hasManagementAdvice>Use cautiously. The doctor may monitor treatment response and adjust therapy if needed.</hasManagementAdvice>
    <hasReference rdf:resource="http://example.org/ontology#R165"/>
    <interactsWith rdf:resource="http://example.org/ontology#S178"/>
  </rdf:Description>
  <rdf:Description rdf:about="http://example.org/ontology#ITN094">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://example.org/ontology#Interaction"/>
    <rdfs:label>ITN094</rdfs:label>
    <hasClinicalEffects>Increased plasma levels, risk of toxicity</hasClinicalEffects>
    <hasInteractionDescription>When trimethoprim is administered simultaneously with drugs that form cations at physiological pH, and are also partly excreted by active renal secretion (e.g. procainamide, amantadine), there is the possibility of competitive inhibition of this process which may lead to an increase in plasma concentration of one or both of the drugs.</hasInteractionDescription>
    <hasManagementAdvice>Monitor drug levels. Watch for increased plasma concentrations.</hasManagementAdvice>
    <hasReference rdf:resource="http://example.org/ontology#R035"/>
    <interactsWith rdf:resource="http://example.org/ontology#S068"/>
  </rdf:Description>
